According to Section 3.12 of Transport Canada's Aeronautical Information Manual (AIM), an aircraft operated in Instrument Flight Rules (IFR) flight shall carry an amount of fuel that is sufficient to allow the aircraft:

(a) In the case of a propeller-driven aeroplane, 
(b) To fly to and execute an approach and a missed approach at the destination aerodrome, 
(c) To fly to and land at the alternate aerodrome, and then to fly for 45 minutes.

Section 3.12 also states that when flying IFR in airspace under the jurisdiction of Canadian ATC, use of the phrase "Cancelling IFR" results in ATC discontinuing the provision of IFR separation, but it does not automatically close the flight plan or itinerary. Therefore, alerting service with regard to SAR notification is still active and based on the information submitted in the original flight plan or itinerary.

Additionally, Section 3.12.2 states that an aircraft shall carry sufficient fuel to meet the requirements of section 602.88, which specifies that the fuel required for a flight includes:

(a) Taxiing and foreseeable delays prior to takeoff;
(b) Meteorological conditions;
(c) Foreseeable air traffic routings and traffic delays;
(d) Landing at a suitable aerodrome in the event of loss of cabin pressurization or, in the case of a multi-engined aircraft, failure of any engine, at the most critical point during the flight;

According to Section 6.3.2.1 of the Canadian Aviation Regulations (TC AIM), if a pilot experiences a two-way communications failure, they should:

(i) immediately climb to and maintain the appropriate minimum IFR altitude until arrival at the fix, route or airway specified in the clearance.

(ii) if being vectored, by the direct route from the point of communications failure to the fix, route, or airway specified in the vector clearance;
(iii) in the absence of an assigned route, by the route that ATC has advised may be expected in a further clearance;
